WEBVTT

00:08.942 --> 00:10.644
‐ My unloading time is at 2:00, and that Brandon Keyser
is always blocking me.

00:10.677 --> 00:12.746
‐ You're Percy's ex, right?

00:12.779 --> 00:15.015
‐ I'm married now.
I got a kid.

00:15.048 --> 00:16.483
‐ As far as Percy is concerned,

00:16.517 --> 00:18.785
you're the only innocent person
in this house.

00:18.819 --> 00:20.420
‐ You realize, whoever it is,

00:20.454 --> 00:23.156
there's a good chance
it'll be someone you know.

00:23.190 --> 00:24.424
‐ Whatever you find,

00:24.458 --> 00:26.393
I'd appreciate
you coming to me first.

00:26.426 --> 00:28.662
‐ Someone broke
into our kitchen last night.

00:28.695 --> 00:30.230
We'll be bleeding money
for weeks.

00:30.264 --> 00:32.332
‐ Payback
for the lobster traps?

00:32.366 --> 00:34.001
‐ My dad just takes it
over and over.

00:34.034 --> 00:35.369
At least I did something.

00:35.402 --> 00:37.638
‐ Percy didn't do this
to herself.

00:37.671 --> 00:39.473
Someone's to blame for this.

00:39.506 --> 00:41.475
She would have come
to me first.

00:41.508 --> 00:44.077
‐ Two boats pulled
together that way.

00:44.111 --> 00:45.512
Anything strange about it?

00:45.546 --> 00:46.647
‐ That's a Keyser boat.

00:46.680 --> 00:48.549
‐ Percy said
that she was responsible

00:48.582 --> 00:50.217
for somebody's death.

00:50.250 --> 00:54.221
Do you know if that
person's name was Valerie?

00:54.254 --> 00:56.123
‐ I've never seen that before.

00:56.156 --> 00:57.291
‐ If you don't stop,

00:57.324 --> 00:59.493
you're gonna end up
doing what I did.

00:59.526 --> 01:01.595
‐ Maybe that's what I deserve.

01:01.628 --> 01:03.664
‐ He's not turning.

01:03.697 --> 01:07.467
Brandon?
Oh, my God.

01:07.501 --> 01:09.736
‐ He took a bullet in the back
of his head.

01:14.107 --> 01:17.044
[dramatic music]

01:17.077 --> 01:24.184
♪ ♪

01:32.125 --> 01:35.395
[ambient music]

01:35.429 --> 01:36.663
‐ All right, I'm going
to need everyone

01:36.697 --> 01:41.602
to take a step back, please.

01:41.635 --> 01:45.539
Ms. Muldoon.

01:45.572 --> 01:47.541
Please.

01:47.574 --> 01:54.147
♪ ♪

01:54.181 --> 01:56.450
‐ Uh, it's a white male,
late 20s,

01:56.483 --> 02:00.320
last name Keyser,
first name's Brandon.

02:00.354 --> 02:02.656
♪ ♪

02:02.689 --> 02:07.327
No, it, uh, looks
like a homicide.

02:07.361 --> 02:08.629
We didn't touch anything,
of course.

02:08.662 --> 02:10.531
♪ ♪

02:10.564 --> 02:12.666
Well, I could really use
the support on this.

02:12.699 --> 02:14.334
We'll can it
till you get here.

02:14.368 --> 02:16.203
♪ ♪

02:16.236 --> 02:17.638
Okay.

02:17.671 --> 02:19.473
Uh...

02:19.506 --> 02:22.743
Portland Homicide crew
are on their way.

02:22.776 --> 02:26.413
‐ Okay.

02:26.446 --> 02:28.448
‐ [sighs]

02:28.482 --> 02:31.018
‐ You gonna be all right?

02:31.051 --> 02:34.354
‐ Yeah. Yeah.

02:34.388 --> 02:35.656
This isn't supposed
to happen here.

02:35.689 --> 02:37.424
It's just not.

02:37.457 --> 02:39.526
[cell phone buzzing]

02:39.560 --> 02:42.196
Oh, God, it's the local paper.

02:42.229 --> 02:45.766
‐ Why don't you take it?
I'll catch up with you later.

02:45.799 --> 02:53.073
♪ ♪

03:00.147 --> 03:03.250
‐ Brandon just became a father.
Do you know that?

03:03.283 --> 03:04.218
‐ No.

03:04.251 --> 03:10.123
‐ Three months ago.
His mother‐‐oh, Belle.

03:10.157 --> 03:11.325
It's going to break her.

03:14.661 --> 03:17.097
‐ What is it with those guys?

03:17.130 --> 03:20.734
‐ Oh, forget about them.
They think you're a Jonah.

03:21.301 --> 03:23.270
‐ Swallowed by a whale?
That guy?

03:23.303 --> 03:27.207
‐ No. [laughs]

03:27.241 --> 03:28.609
It's a bringer of bad luck.

03:28.642 --> 03:31.111
Fishermen are superstitious.

03:35.582 --> 03:37.117
This thing with Brandon

03:37.150 --> 03:39.453
has something
to do with Percy, doesn't it?

03:41.588 --> 03:43.290
‐ I don't know.

03:47.127 --> 03:52.599
I found a pack of nicotine gum
on Brandon's body.

03:52.633 --> 03:56.503
It was the same brand
that I found on that beach,

03:56.537 --> 03:58.238
where the security footage

03:58.272 --> 04:01.341
showed Percy
with whoever it was.

04:01.375 --> 04:03.143
‐ Do you think Brandon
might've been the one

04:03.177 --> 04:05.312
who followed Percy
up to the bluff?

04:07.481 --> 04:12.286
‐ I don't know.

04:12.319 --> 04:15.422
You know if they had
any problems recently?

04:15.455 --> 04:18.025
You know, did you hear
anybody mention anything?

04:18.425 --> 04:21.195
‐ Well, I know he still
had feelings for her.

04:21.228 --> 04:24.398
She broke it off so suddenly.
But still...

04:24.431 --> 04:27.534
[uneasy music]

04:28.135 --> 04:31.405
‐ I really need to see
the family and talk to them

04:31.438 --> 04:35.075
before the Portland guys
get here and get in the away.

04:35.108 --> 04:37.044
‐ I can give Belle a call.

04:38.579 --> 04:42.382
If she sold him back something,
I'll know it.

04:47.554 --> 04:50.057
‐ Why did you leave at 3:00
in the morning today?

04:50.090 --> 04:53.227
‐ We all go out that early.
That's what fishermen do.

04:53.260 --> 04:55.462
‐ Hmm.
Well, harbor records reports

04:55.495 --> 04:58.265
say you usually
don't get out till 5:00 a. m.,

04:58.298 --> 04:59.499
so why the early departure?

04:59.533 --> 05:01.001
‐ I was up early.

05:01.034 --> 05:03.270
I thought I might
as well get a good start.

05:03.303 --> 05:07.074
‐ So what'd you see out there?
‐ Ocean.

05:08.242 --> 05:11.545
‐ What about other boats?
‐ It's a big area.

05:11.578 --> 05:12.646
It was dark.

05:12.679 --> 05:14.648
‐ And the moon
was near full that night.

05:14.681 --> 05:16.583
It was cloudy.

05:17.217 --> 05:18.519
‐ You've been doing this
for quite a while.

05:18.552 --> 05:19.786
‐ Hey, Josh.
‐ Hey.

05:19.820 --> 05:21.255
They're in the middle
of an interview.

05:21.288 --> 05:22.523
‐ I need you
to be straight with me.

05:22.556 --> 05:23.757
‐ Oh, no.

05:23.790 --> 05:26.226
Mike Lam?
You're going after him now?

05:26.260 --> 05:27.661
Is this because his traps
were on Brandon's boat?

05:27.694 --> 05:29.196
He's the one?

05:29.229 --> 05:30.631
‐ We tracked Brandon's GPS.

05:30.664 --> 05:33.667
He was anchored right
where Mike Lam has his traps.

05:33.700 --> 05:35.636
‐ It doesn't mean anything.

05:35.669 --> 05:37.471
‐ Mike Lam's GPS
puts him there too.

05:37.504 --> 05:40.307
Same time.
We know they crossed paths.

05:45.479 --> 05:47.014
‐ Your son, CJ,

05:47.047 --> 05:48.615
allegedly cut traps
belonging to the Muldoons.

05:48.649 --> 05:50.150
‐ There's no proof of that.

05:50.184 --> 05:51.585
‐ But you've been
hassled before

05:51.618 --> 05:53.453
by the Keysers
and the Muldoons.

05:53.487 --> 05:55.556
I hear it's not exactly
a friendly vibe

05:55.589 --> 05:57.057
between you and them.

05:57.090 --> 05:58.425
It must get pretty frustrating

05:58.458 --> 06:01.061
having your lines
cut over and over again.

06:01.094 --> 06:02.129
I'd be angry.
I'd wanna do something‐‐

06:02.162 --> 06:03.630
‐ Harry‐‐
‐ I want to talk to you.

06:03.664 --> 06:04.765
‐ Sorry about this.
I'm...

06:04.798 --> 06:06.466
‐ You got the wrong guy.

06:06.500 --> 06:07.634
‐ Let's step outside.
‐ You're making a mistake.

06:07.668 --> 06:09.136
‐ Harry‐‐

06:09.169 --> 06:10.337
‐ Forensics is going
to come back,

06:10.370 --> 06:12.506
and the report will show
that Brandon Keyser

06:12.539 --> 06:16.109
was shot at close range,
probably with a .22,

06:16.143 --> 06:17.778
in the back of the head.

06:17.811 --> 06:19.446
That is a premeditated hit.

06:19.479 --> 06:20.647
‐ Who is this?

06:20.681 --> 06:22.049
‐ That is not this guy.

06:22.082 --> 06:24.017
‐ This is Harry Ambrose.
He found the body.

06:24.051 --> 06:25.652
‐ What, you think Keyser
would let Mike Lam, here,

06:25.686 --> 06:28.755
somebody that he sabotaged,
somebody that he hates,

06:28.789 --> 06:31.491
he would have him on board
and then turn his back to him?

06:31.525 --> 06:35.662
It doesn't make sense.
You can't prosecute with this.

06:35.696 --> 06:38.198
‐ Harry, outside!

06:38.232 --> 06:40.567
‐ And it's a waste of time.
‐ Now!

06:40.601 --> 06:43.537
[uneasy music]

06:43.570 --> 06:48.008
♪ ♪

06:48.041 --> 06:49.409
You can't just barge in on me
like that, Harry.

06:49.443 --> 06:51.078
That's a detective
from Portland.

06:51.111 --> 06:52.246
‐ This is your case.

06:52.279 --> 06:53.413
‐ No, it's not.
‐ It is.

06:53.447 --> 06:54.648
‐ Josh and I
are taking a backseat.

06:54.681 --> 06:56.083
This one's over our heads.

06:56.116 --> 06:57.284
‐ Don't let that guy,

06:57.317 --> 06:59.152
that Portland guy,
distract you.

06:59.186 --> 07:01.488
Brandon's murder‐‐
I think...

07:01.522 --> 07:03.423
that's somebody
covering their tracks.

07:03.457 --> 07:07.494
They feel pressured.
We're getting close on this.

07:10.097 --> 07:11.365
‐ I really appreciate

07:11.398 --> 07:15.335
everything
you've done for us, Harry,

07:15.369 --> 07:17.638
but you disrespected me
in there.

07:17.671 --> 07:20.274
♪ ♪

07:20.307 --> 07:21.775
I'm sorry.

07:21.808 --> 07:24.411
There's no room
for you on this anymore.

07:24.444 --> 07:26.647
I need you to go.

07:26.680 --> 07:32.753
♪ ♪

07:32.786 --> 07:35.055
Sorry about that.

07:35.088 --> 07:37.191
♪ ♪

07:40.794 --> 07:43.463
‐ Hey.

07:43.497 --> 07:45.666
We loved him.

07:45.699 --> 07:49.336
My boys and I loved him.
You know that.

07:49.369 --> 07:54.141
And we love you and Kat
and her little baby.

07:54.174 --> 07:56.777
We're going to be there
for you,

07:56.810 --> 07:59.146
just the way
you've always been for us.

07:59.179 --> 08:01.415
‐ I just can't believe it.

08:01.448 --> 08:04.251
‐ I know.

08:04.284 --> 08:07.020
I know.

08:07.054 --> 08:08.088
‐ Call me for anything.

08:08.121 --> 08:09.656
‐ I will.
Thank you.

08:09.690 --> 08:15.229
‐ I love you, Kat.

08:15.262 --> 08:16.663
‐ Uh...

08:16.697 --> 08:18.632
there's never a good time
for this,

08:18.665 --> 08:20.367
but I had a few questions.

08:20.400 --> 08:24.104
You might guess we're trying
to figure this all out.

08:24.137 --> 08:27.541
‐ You're that detective, right?
You found Brandon?

08:27.574 --> 08:29.009
‐ Yeah. Yeah.

08:29.042 --> 08:31.278
‐ Did they arrest
that Chinese guy yet?

08:32.145 --> 08:35.182
‐ Mike Lam.
He is only a suspect right now.

08:35.215 --> 08:37.084
He hasn't been charged
with anything.

08:37.117 --> 08:38.452
‐ I told Brandon this shit
would bite him

08:38.485 --> 08:39.486
in the ass one day.

08:39.520 --> 08:42.422
All these guys fighting
over their fucking traps.

08:42.456 --> 08:43.757
‐ Right. Yeah.

08:43.790 --> 08:46.460
But I think
there's more to it than that.

08:47.828 --> 08:50.397
Did he ever mention trouble

08:50.430 --> 08:52.599
that he might have
with anybody else?

08:52.633 --> 08:55.135
‐ Brandon was never in trouble
for anyone.

08:55.169 --> 08:57.638
He was a good man,
an honest man.

08:57.671 --> 09:00.474
‐ A little strange.

09:00.507 --> 09:02.176
Last night, he was out alone.

09:03.177 --> 09:05.179
He didn't have a crew.

09:07.114 --> 09:09.349
You have any idea why that is?

09:09.383 --> 09:12.619
‐ To be honest, I'm surprised
he was out on the water at all.

09:12.653 --> 09:14.621
‐ How's that?
‐ I don't know.

09:14.655 --> 09:16.290
Usually, he'd be down island

09:16.323 --> 09:18.225
somewhere else,
entertaining himself...

09:18.258 --> 09:19.226
‐ Kat!

09:19.259 --> 09:21.061
‐ While I sit here
pumping milk.

09:21.094 --> 09:23.530
‐ You are not starting
with this, not now!

09:23.564 --> 09:25.465
‐ I'm just saying what's true,
all right?

09:25.499 --> 09:27.167
‐ Show some respect
for my son's memory.

09:27.201 --> 09:28.735
‐ Just because he's dead

09:28.769 --> 09:30.737
doesn't mean he wasn't screwing
half of Hanover, all right?

09:30.771 --> 09:32.472
‐ Kat!

09:32.506 --> 09:34.241
She lost her son.

09:34.675 --> 09:37.644
[ambient music]

09:37.678 --> 09:40.514
♪ ♪

09:40.547 --> 09:44.384
‐ [breathing raggedly]

09:44.418 --> 09:47.721
Look, just talk
to his second mate.

09:48.522 --> 09:51.425
Brandon had him cover for him
every time I called.

09:51.458 --> 09:54.628
Typical guy code shit.

09:54.661 --> 09:57.464
‐ Kat, was Brandon

09:57.497 --> 10:00.634
ever involved
with someone named Valerie?

10:00.667 --> 10:04.238
‐ [scoffs] Shit.

10:04.271 --> 10:08.242
I don't know.
Probably.

10:08.275 --> 10:10.677
‐ That's enough!

10:11.578 --> 10:15.549
‐ Well, all right.
I need to change a diaper.

10:15.582 --> 10:20.254
♪ ♪

10:20.287 --> 10:24.658
‐ I know what it feels like.

10:24.691 --> 10:28.362
I do.

10:28.395 --> 10:31.431
We have to find out
who did this to our children.

10:33.567 --> 10:34.635
‐ What do you mean?

10:34.668 --> 10:36.737
‐ Brandon and Percy

10:36.770 --> 10:39.540
were together
the night she disappeared.

10:39.573 --> 10:43.710
There's security footage with
them on it by the Dory Shop.

10:45.078 --> 10:48.448
‐ Doing what?
‐ I don't‐‐it's hard to tell.

10:48.482 --> 10:53.053
But they had
some kind of disagreement.

10:53.620 --> 10:56.723
Did he ever mention
anything like that to you?

10:57.291 --> 10:59.226
‐ No.

10:59.259 --> 11:02.462
What does that have to do
with anything?

11:02.496 --> 11:04.097
‐ Well, right after that,

11:04.131 --> 11:07.234
somebody followed
Percy to the cliff.

11:07.267 --> 11:08.368
Maybe it was Brandon.

11:08.402 --> 11:10.070
‐ What are you saying?

11:10.103 --> 11:12.139
‐ We're just trying
to understand what happened.

11:12.172 --> 11:14.608
And if we know
what they were talking about‐‐

11:14.641 --> 11:17.644
‐ You think my Brandon
did what?

11:17.678 --> 11:20.314
‐ Oh, Belle.
‐ The gall on you.

11:20.347 --> 11:23.150
You come here spouting
your bullshit about our bond

11:23.183 --> 11:26.186
and how you're here for us,
and then you accuse my son?

11:26.220 --> 11:29.489
‐ No, we're not accusing‐‐
‐ Get out!

11:29.523 --> 11:31.658
You goddamn Muldoons.

11:31.692 --> 11:34.628
It's always about you,
isn't it?

11:34.661 --> 11:36.063
Get the hell out.

11:36.096 --> 11:37.397
‐ Come on, Belle.

11:37.431 --> 11:38.665
‐ We're just trying to‐‐

11:38.699 --> 11:42.002
‐ Did you forget
where the fucking door is?

11:42.035 --> 11:44.471
‐ Come on, Belle.
Let's go.

11:58.552 --> 12:00.020
‐ When things calm down,
I'll contact Kat Keyser about Brandon's permit,

12:00.053 --> 12:01.388
offer to buy her out.

12:01.421 --> 12:03.290
‐ Buy her out?
With what?

12:03.323 --> 12:04.191
‐ Oh, we'll figure it out.

12:04.224 --> 12:06.126
But when we get
that groundfish permit,

12:06.159 --> 12:08.028
we won't be so dependent
on the lobster haul.

12:08.061 --> 12:09.096
‐ There's just no way
you could compete

12:09.129 --> 12:10.664
with the Portland outfits
anymore.

12:10.697 --> 12:12.232
‐ So then we won't.
We'll sell local.

12:12.266 --> 12:13.534
‐ Keysers have been
losing money

12:13.567 --> 12:15.102
on that track for years.

12:15.135 --> 12:17.337
And you want to sink money
that we don't even have?

12:17.371 --> 12:19.106
‐ What is your problem?

12:19.139 --> 12:22.242
‐ It's a dying business.
All of it.

12:24.111 --> 12:27.214
And you know it.

12:27.247 --> 12:30.584
We all do.

12:30.617 --> 12:34.421
‐ You're talking permits
at a time like this?

12:35.122 --> 12:36.557
‐ Just trying to think ahead.

12:36.590 --> 12:39.493
‐ This whole thing
is connected to Percy.

12:39.526 --> 12:41.228
We should be talking
about that.

12:41.261 --> 12:46.133
Brandon's the guy in the video.
He was with her.

12:47.801 --> 12:50.637
‐ Brandon was the guy
on the docks that night?

12:50.671 --> 12:52.239
‐ How do you even know that?

12:54.308 --> 12:58.612
Ambrose!
Mom, that guy's a wrong number.

12:58.645 --> 13:00.113
What are you still doing
running around with him?

13:00.147 --> 13:00.981
I told him‐‐

13:01.014 --> 13:04.218
‐ He's right about this,
and I know it.

13:04.251 --> 13:06.620
‐ The guy is nuts,
and he's fucking paranoid.

13:06.653 --> 13:10.257
‐ What would Brandon
have wanted with Percy?

13:10.290 --> 13:12.726
‐ This has nothing to do
with Percy.

13:12.759 --> 13:15.696
[uneasy music]

13:15.729 --> 13:22.970
♪ ♪

13:27.140 --> 13:33.046
Ma, we stopped
with the trapping bullshit.

13:33.080 --> 13:33.981
We did.

13:34.014 --> 13:36.750
And I told Brandon to stop,
and he didn't.

13:36.783 --> 13:39.119
So Mike must have
finally snapped.

13:39.152 --> 13:41.755
But...

13:41.788 --> 13:47.594
you need to start
accepting some things here.

13:47.628 --> 13:52.399
I know it's hard,

13:52.432 --> 13:55.469
but we might...

13:55.502 --> 14:01.775
never know
why she did what she did,

14:01.808 --> 14:03.677
and maybe that's for the best.

14:07.447 --> 14:11.285
‐ How could you say that?

14:11.318 --> 14:14.221
‐ Because the Percy
who came back from the mainland

14:14.254 --> 14:19.293
was not our little girl,
not anymore.

14:19.326 --> 14:23.096
I tried.

14:23.130 --> 14:29.970
We all did, but, you know,
she was going away from us...

14:34.575 --> 14:37.578
And you know it.

14:37.611 --> 14:44.685
♪ ♪

15:01.635 --> 15:05.272
‐ Blood, sweat, and tears solve
problems, not complaining.

15:05.305 --> 15:08.075
‐ But there is
a scarcity issue, Ma.

15:08.108 --> 15:09.376
And nothing's going
to change that.

15:09.409 --> 15:11.612
‐ He's been working extra hours
every day.

15:11.645 --> 15:13.714
He's practically dead
when he gets home.

15:13.747 --> 15:15.382
‐ And this one's pulling in
about a trap a day

15:15.415 --> 15:16.550
at this point.

15:16.583 --> 15:17.784
‐ Fuck off.

15:17.818 --> 15:19.520
‐ Well, if that's the way
it is,

15:19.553 --> 15:21.121
I'll go back out myself.

15:21.154 --> 15:23.123
‐ No, you're not going to have
another stroke.

15:23.156 --> 15:24.691
You're not.
And besides, the guys that are

15:24.725 --> 15:26.426
coming in from the coast‐‐
they don't play nice.

15:26.460 --> 15:28.028
It's getting dangerous.

15:28.061 --> 15:29.696
‐ Oh, we're just going
to have to fight it.

15:29.730 --> 15:31.798
These are our waters.
They need to know that.

15:31.832 --> 15:33.534
We were here first.

15:33.567 --> 15:36.603
‐ That's just not true.

15:36.637 --> 15:38.372
The waters aren't ours.
That's bullshit.

15:38.405 --> 15:40.674
‐ Hey, don't talk to
your grandma like that.

15:42.376 --> 15:44.011
‐ What makes you say that?

15:45.112 --> 15:48.448
‐ Our family didn't come
from Ireland until what?

15:48.482 --> 15:49.650
The 1850s?

15:49.683 --> 15:52.286
‐ Yeah.
The famine.

15:52.319 --> 15:56.623
‐ Right, so there were people
already here,

15:56.657 --> 15:57.791
all the Wabanaki tribes,

15:57.824 --> 15:59.259
people who had been here
a long time.

15:59.293 --> 16:01.195
‐ For fuck's sake.
‐ Let her talk.

16:06.800 --> 16:09.203
‐ You can't say the waters
belong to us.

16:09.236 --> 16:12.105
We stole them,
and then we pillaged them.

16:12.139 --> 16:13.740
We're the reason
there's a scarcity issue.

16:13.774 --> 16:17.344
‐ We never stole anything.
There was nothing here.

16:17.377 --> 16:20.547
Your great‐grandfather built
this company from nothing.

16:20.581 --> 16:23.016
‐ There were people here

16:23.050 --> 16:25.052
living in balance with nature.

16:25.085 --> 16:29.256
They just didn't care
about making money.

16:29.289 --> 16:31.158
‐ What's gotten into you?

16:32.693 --> 16:36.763
You never had a problem
with any of this before,

16:36.797 --> 16:39.132
and now we're pillaging?

16:39.166 --> 16:42.236
‐ I'm just trying to see things
as they are, Grams.

16:44.137 --> 16:47.007
‐ Then why don't you start
by giving up your room

16:47.040 --> 16:50.110
and your car
and the food on your plate,

16:50.143 --> 16:53.547
and you'll see things
as they are, hmm?

16:57.117 --> 16:59.253
Sean, make another pot
of coffee.

16:59.286 --> 17:06.193
♪ ♪

17:22.376 --> 17:24.611
‐ [speaking Spanish]‐ Raffa?
‐ He's right there.

17:24.645 --> 17:27.614
‐ Okay.

17:27.648 --> 17:29.082
Hey.

17:29.116 --> 17:32.519
‐ Hey.
‐ Raffa Dominguez, right?

17:32.553 --> 17:36.089
I'm Harry Ambrose, working
on the Percy Muldoon case.

17:36.123 --> 17:38.225
‐ Yeah, Raffa.
What's up?

17:38.258 --> 17:40.093
[upbeat Spanish music playing]

17:40.127 --> 17:43.163
‐ You're friends with Brandon,
right?

17:43.197 --> 17:44.565
‐ Well, he's my boss.

17:47.634 --> 17:52.172
‐ How often was it
that you crewed for him?

17:52.206 --> 17:54.107
‐ Almost every time
he goes out.

17:54.141 --> 17:58.111
‐ What about last night?

17:58.145 --> 18:00.614
‐ No, man.
No, not last night.

18:00.647 --> 18:02.249
‐ You sure?
‐ Yeah. Yeah, not last night.

18:02.282 --> 18:04.351
You can ask around.
I was here last night.

18:07.321 --> 18:12.259
‐ Did you know Brandon
was having an affair?

18:12.292 --> 18:13.560
‐ I don't bother myself

18:13.594 --> 18:15.295
with other people's
personal business.

18:15.329 --> 18:17.764
‐ It's just, his wife says

18:17.798 --> 18:21.468
that you would know
who he might've been seeing.

18:21.502 --> 18:26.173
‐ Sorry, man.

18:26.206 --> 18:29.610
‐ You want to think about this.

18:29.643 --> 18:33.547
There's a homicide unit
in from Portland.

18:33.580 --> 18:36.683
And the lead detective‐‐
he's got a list,

18:36.717 --> 18:39.386
and they'll probably do
a full rundown on you

18:39.419 --> 18:43.223
and your friends
and your status here.

18:43.257 --> 18:45.726
‐ Are you threatening me?

18:45.759 --> 18:48.295
‐ No.
It's just‐‐

18:48.328 --> 18:51.164
I've been around too long.

18:51.198 --> 18:54.668
And the sooner that I can get
to whoever it is

18:54.701 --> 18:56.603
that's behind this,
the sooner that I‐‐

18:56.637 --> 18:59.206
this whole investigation
is going to shut down.

19:01.108 --> 19:05.078
‐ You know where I'm from?
Honduras.

19:05.112 --> 19:07.214
You know what they call it?

19:07.247 --> 19:10.083
The murder capital
of the world.

19:10.117 --> 19:13.287
At least one of them, anyway.

19:13.320 --> 19:16.056
I was up to my neck
in that shit.

19:16.089 --> 19:19.193
I'm a paramedic,
and a good one.

19:19.226 --> 19:21.428
I just couldn't take it
anymore, man.

19:22.696 --> 19:25.065
I was breaking.

19:27.768 --> 19:30.437
This is why I need to stay.

19:30.470 --> 19:33.240
And this is why I'm here,
me and my wife.

19:35.242 --> 19:36.476
You know what I'm saying?

19:38.712 --> 19:41.381
‐ I don't want to make
your life more difficult.

19:41.782 --> 19:46.386
It's not why I'm here.

19:46.420 --> 19:48.655
‐ Okay.

19:48.689 --> 19:52.559
About a couple of weeks ago,
I got a call from Brandon.

19:52.593 --> 19:53.827
Hey, boss.

19:53.861 --> 19:56.630
‐ Dude, you're saving my life.
I didn't know who else to call.

19:56.663 --> 19:58.599
My friend here had
a little accident,

19:58.632 --> 20:00.567
and she won't let me take her
to the hospital...

20:00.601 --> 20:01.335
‐ You all right?

20:01.368 --> 20:03.470
‐ So will you take
a look at her?

20:03.770 --> 20:06.139
‐ [speaking Spanish]
‐ Uh‐huh.

20:10.377 --> 20:12.079
‐ Yeah.
I mean, we were just out

20:12.112 --> 20:15.148
by Dublin Point,
and she slipped.

20:15.182 --> 20:18.685
♪ ♪

20:18.719 --> 20:21.121
‐ [winces]

20:24.291 --> 20:27.628
‐ Yeah, I mean, you can't tell
anyone about this, okay?

20:27.661 --> 20:30.197
I mean, no one,
especially not Kat.

20:30.230 --> 20:34.401
You know, just fix her up

20:34.434 --> 20:38.472
and forget
all about this, okay?

20:38.505 --> 20:40.707
♪ ♪

20:40.741 --> 20:43.744
‐ I couldn't tell you if she
was from around here or not,

20:43.777 --> 20:45.746
but I knew something was wrong.

20:45.779 --> 20:47.080
‐ How's that?

20:47.114 --> 20:49.216
‐ Well, just the way
he was acting.

20:49.249 --> 20:52.219
And her wound
wasn't made by rocks.

20:52.252 --> 20:54.454
I dug a piece of ring nail
out of her foot.

20:56.256 --> 20:57.758
‐ Ring nail?
What's that?

20:57.791 --> 20:59.726
‐ They use it to build boats.

20:59.760 --> 21:04.665
It was rusted
with rotten wood splinters.

21:04.698 --> 21:06.466
I did my best to get her alone

21:06.500 --> 21:08.669
so I could ask her
what was going on,

21:08.702 --> 21:10.337
but then someone else
showed up.

21:12.206 --> 21:15.442
‐ Who?

21:15.475 --> 21:17.344
‐ Brandon!

21:17.377 --> 21:19.513
‐ Shit.
She fucking followed me?

21:19.546 --> 21:21.348
‐ I need to talk to you.

21:21.381 --> 21:22.749
‐ Uh, you know what?
That's good enough.

21:22.783 --> 21:24.084
‐ Wait. Wait.

21:24.117 --> 21:24.918
I still have
to put a bandage on.

21:24.952 --> 21:27.054
‐ I know, man. I know.
I can do that.

21:27.087 --> 21:30.324
‐ Brandon, hold on a minute.

21:30.357 --> 21:33.160
[engine turns over]

21:33.193 --> 21:36.263
Brandon...

21:36.296 --> 21:38.665
Who was that woman with him?

21:38.699 --> 21:40.067
‐ I have no idea.

21:40.100 --> 21:43.070
[ambient music]

21:43.103 --> 21:48.208
♪ ♪

21:48.242 --> 21:50.344
‐ So Percy saw her too.

21:53.780 --> 21:56.617
The woman's name‐‐

21:56.650 --> 21:58.685
was it Valerie?

21:58.719 --> 22:03.156
‐ I don't know.
She was too scared to say.

22:03.190 --> 22:05.192
‐ Did you report this?

22:05.225 --> 22:11.365
♪ ♪

22:11.398 --> 22:14.568
‐ People like me
don't get to go to the police.

22:14.601 --> 22:21.508
♪ ♪

22:38.825 --> 22:40.594
[door latch clicks]
‐ [speaking Cantonese]

22:55.242 --> 22:56.577
‐ No.

23:03.383 --> 23:06.353
[somber music]

23:06.386 --> 23:13.460
♪ ♪

23:57.104 --> 23:58.572
‐ Meg, I don't even know
how to do that.

23:58.605 --> 24:00.574
‐ What do you mean?
You just reopen the case.

24:00.607 --> 24:02.342
‐ With what?
We don't have any leads.

24:02.376 --> 24:04.578
There's no autopsy report
for Percy.

24:04.611 --> 24:06.079
There's nothing
that suggests foul play.

24:06.113 --> 24:08.348
‐ I'm telling you,
Brandon Keyser.

24:08.382 --> 24:10.551
‐ We don't know
who's on that tape.

24:10.584 --> 24:13.654
We don't even know if that tape
means anything at all.

24:14.188 --> 24:15.455
‐ Come on, Lou.

24:15.489 --> 24:17.224
When's the last time
something like this

24:17.257 --> 24:18.559
happened in Clark Harbor?

24:18.592 --> 24:20.294
And it's our Percy and Brandon.

24:20.327 --> 24:21.495
‐ If there's a connection,

24:21.528 --> 24:23.363
Portland will find it,
and so will I.

24:23.397 --> 24:26.033
‐ But you're not looking
for it.

24:26.066 --> 24:28.669
You have to look for it.

24:28.702 --> 24:32.573
‐ Well, but you gotta
let me do my job.

24:38.779 --> 24:40.614
‐ When's the detective
coming back?

24:40.647 --> 24:43.116
‐ I told you
he's busy off‐site.

24:43.150 --> 24:44.618
It might be a while.

24:44.651 --> 24:46.753
‐ Yo, like, this can't wait.
It's about Brandon.

24:46.787 --> 24:49.489
‐ What is it?
I'll relay.

24:49.523 --> 24:51.325
‐ No, I'm not talking to you.

24:53.093 --> 24:55.696
‐ Whatever.

24:55.729 --> 24:59.299
It's not going
to change anything anyway.

24:59.333 --> 25:02.035
‐ My father is innocent,
and you know it.

25:06.373 --> 25:08.342
Fuck you!

25:25.592 --> 25:27.461
‐ You know something
about Brandon.

25:29.162 --> 25:30.297
I was at the station.

25:30.330 --> 25:34.234
I saw you talking
to that deputy.

25:34.268 --> 25:35.502
‐ It's nothing.

25:35.536 --> 25:38.338
‐ Would you tell me
what you know?

25:38.372 --> 25:43.577
This has something to do
with Percy somehow.

25:43.610 --> 25:45.579
‐ Why should I tell you
anything?

25:46.079 --> 25:49.082
‐ Look, I know things

25:49.116 --> 25:51.351
have been bad
between our families,

25:51.385 --> 25:56.123
but you have to understand, we
were desperate to find Percy,

25:56.156 --> 25:58.759
at least to know she was safe.

25:58.792 --> 26:01.695
We were wrong about you.

26:01.728 --> 26:05.766
I know that now.
I'm sorry.

26:05.799 --> 26:08.569
[ambient music]

26:08.602 --> 26:14.174
‐ I would never have hurt her.
I loved her.

26:14.208 --> 26:21.315
♪ ♪

26:22.316 --> 26:24.585
‐ Well, I believe you.

26:32.759 --> 26:37.364
Please tell me what you know,
for Percy's sake.

26:41.268 --> 26:42.569
‐ You tell me this.

26:45.239 --> 26:47.241
Who has Brandon
been meeting with at the pier

26:47.274 --> 26:49.610
in the early mornings?

26:49.643 --> 26:51.778
Some boat from off‐island.

26:51.812 --> 26:53.347
‐ I don't know
what you're talking about.

26:53.380 --> 26:54.615
‐ Yeah, well, every two weeks
or so,

26:54.648 --> 26:57.484
my dad and I‐‐we see them.

26:57.518 --> 27:00.354
Your sons are involved
with everything Brandon does,

27:00.387 --> 27:05.092
which means you must know too.

27:05.125 --> 27:08.228
What are they doing, hmm?
Side deals on illegal hauls?

27:08.262 --> 27:09.463
‐ No, wait a minute.

27:09.496 --> 27:11.198
If my sons were involved
in anything illegal,

27:11.231 --> 27:12.666
I would know.

27:12.699 --> 27:17.204
‐ Well, Brandon's got some kind
of deal with those men.

27:17.237 --> 27:20.207
‐ How do you know?

27:20.240 --> 27:22.609
CJ, please tell me.

27:31.518 --> 27:35.022
‐ I started following Brandon
to see what he was up to.

27:35.055 --> 27:37.024
I wanted to catch him.

27:37.057 --> 27:42.529
I wanted to find some dirt
on him, your sons too.

27:42.563 --> 27:44.298
After all the stuff
they did to my family,

27:44.331 --> 27:46.200
I thought I could use it
against them.

27:49.369 --> 27:51.471
‐ So what did you see?

27:51.505 --> 27:55.342
♪ ♪

27:55.375 --> 27:59.079
‐ I followed Brandon
to the disposal yard.

27:59.112 --> 28:01.481
I saw him meeting up
with these two guys.

28:01.515 --> 28:06.286
♪ ♪

28:06.320 --> 28:08.055
‐ Hey.
‐ Hey, man.

28:08.088 --> 28:10.090
‐ Hey.
‐ So what's this all about?

28:10.123 --> 28:12.292
Oh! [coughs]

28:12.326 --> 28:15.462
‐ When you're told to shut it
down, you shut it down.

28:15.495 --> 28:20.167
Don't fuck with us again,
got it?

28:20.200 --> 28:23.003
‐ It was too dark,
but he thinks they were

28:23.036 --> 28:26.640
the same guys that Brandon
was meeting at the docks.

28:26.673 --> 28:30.310
‐ You know,
that woman that was hurt‐‐

28:30.344 --> 28:32.246
she was with Brandon.

28:32.279 --> 28:37.651
Raffa said he pulled out
of her foot this ring nail.

28:37.684 --> 28:39.353
‐ Ring nail?

28:39.386 --> 28:42.289
You think
she got hurt at the boatyard?

28:42.322 --> 28:45.592
‐ It could be.
You know...

28:45.626 --> 28:49.229
Those two guys and Brandon‐‐

28:49.263 --> 28:52.032
why were they meeting
him there?

28:52.065 --> 28:56.503
‐ Hmm.

28:56.537 --> 28:59.039
You having trouble
with your grill?

28:59.072 --> 29:02.342
‐ Oh, it hasn't really worked
since we got here.

29:02.376 --> 29:03.710
I put it together.

29:03.744 --> 29:06.046
I had to take it apart
three times.

29:06.079 --> 29:08.382
‐ So you think
the fourth time's a charm, eh?

29:09.116 --> 29:10.284
‐ Yeah.

29:10.317 --> 29:13.020
I just promised Sonya
that I'd fix it.

29:14.655 --> 29:19.293
Didn't want to let it slide.

29:19.326 --> 29:21.795
[sighs]

29:21.828 --> 29:25.332
I'd like to take a look
at that boatyard.

29:25.365 --> 29:29.136
‐ A friend of ours owns it,
Don Lanier.

29:29.169 --> 29:32.606
‐ I've seen him.

29:32.639 --> 29:36.710
He was at Percy's wake, right,
and Brandon's?

29:36.743 --> 29:41.748
‐ I could stop by his place,
find out if he knows anything.

29:42.382 --> 29:49.189
‐ Uh... you should know
Raffa also told me

29:49.223 --> 29:51.592
Percy showed up at his house.

29:53.060 --> 29:54.561
She saw that woman
with Brandon,

29:54.595 --> 29:58.098
and he tore off out of there.

29:58.131 --> 30:02.336
It could have been
what started all of this.

30:02.369 --> 30:07.741
‐ I swear, if he wasn't
already dead...

30:07.774 --> 30:11.712
♪ ♪

30:11.745 --> 30:15.148
S...

30:15.182 --> 30:22.055
♪ ♪

30:23.323 --> 30:26.260
[suspenseful music]

30:26.293 --> 30:33.333
♪ ♪

31:39.299 --> 31:40.300
[lively chatter]‐ Hey, hey, hey.

31:40.334 --> 31:42.202
‐ ♪ The heat is down
and the lights are low ♪

31:42.236 --> 31:45.205
♪ The East is buried
in an icy snow ♪

31:45.239 --> 31:48.542
♪ The West is following
crisis rules ♪

31:48.575 --> 31:53.080
♪ They can't go swimming
in their swimming pools ♪

31:53.113 --> 31:55.315
♪ And the tapes go hmm‐mm... ♪

31:55.349 --> 31:56.483
‐ Meg.

31:56.517 --> 31:57.751
‐ I need to talk to you.

31:57.784 --> 32:00.187
‐ Isn't my granddaughter
something?

32:00.220 --> 32:02.623
Ever since she discovered
my old vinyl in the basement.

32:02.656 --> 32:04.625
‐ ♪ Hmm‐mm ♪

32:04.658 --> 32:07.628
‐ Do you know what Brandon
was up to in your boatyard?

32:07.661 --> 32:10.631
[uneasy music]

32:10.664 --> 32:17.671
♪ ♪

32:49.670 --> 32:51.238
‐ [gags]

32:51.271 --> 32:53.473
[flies buzzing]

32:53.507 --> 32:55.209
♪ ♪

32:55.242 --> 32:56.743
Agh.

32:56.777 --> 33:04.084
♪ ♪

33:11.692 --> 33:13.227
‐ Brandon was with a woman

33:13.260 --> 33:15.128
who may have been hurt
in your yard.

33:16.663 --> 33:18.732
‐ Come on, Meg.
The kid just died.

33:18.765 --> 33:20.667
‐ And you're having a party.

33:20.701 --> 33:23.704
‐ I wasn't about to cancel
Ashley's birthday, all right?

33:23.737 --> 33:25.339
And you were invited.

33:25.372 --> 33:26.607
‐ [scoffs]

33:26.640 --> 33:31.211
What was Brandon
doing in your yard?

33:31.245 --> 33:35.349
‐ Well, we all know the kid
had a wandering eye,

33:35.382 --> 33:38.318
and that boatyard's about
as secluded as you can get.

33:38.352 --> 33:39.753
So what do you think
he was doing there?

33:39.786 --> 33:42.256
‐ Last week, two men
attacked him there.

33:44.124 --> 33:47.694
‐ Who told you that?

33:47.728 --> 33:52.032
‐ Someone I know
who saw it firsthand.

33:52.065 --> 33:54.368
‐ And that was?

33:54.401 --> 33:59.039
‐ That's not important.

33:59.072 --> 34:01.408
‐ You're still hanging out
with that detective.

34:03.377 --> 34:05.712
I think he's rubbing off
on you a bit too much.

34:05.746 --> 34:08.215
‐ Brandon may have been
the last person

34:08.248 --> 34:12.619
to see Percy alive,
and he is dead.

34:12.653 --> 34:15.255
It doesn't take
a genius to wonder.

34:15.289 --> 34:22.229
♪ ♪

34:37.377 --> 34:41.215
‐ Look, Meg, I think
what happened with Percy‐‐

34:41.248 --> 34:44.084
it's a damn hard thing
to accept,

34:44.117 --> 34:46.720
and I know you're hurting,
but‐‐

34:46.753 --> 34:48.622
‐ There's something going on,
and you know it.

34:48.655 --> 34:51.225
‐ And I just told you
what it is:

34:51.258 --> 34:53.260
Brandon screwing women
in the dark.

34:53.293 --> 34:56.096
That's it.
‐ Come on, Don.

34:56.129 --> 34:57.764
I've known you for 58 years.

34:57.798 --> 35:00.467
I babysat you
when you were young.

35:00.501 --> 35:02.703
I've watched your kids grow up
and get married

35:02.736 --> 35:04.438
and have kids of their own.

35:04.471 --> 35:07.074
I was spooning broth
into Laurie's mouth

35:07.107 --> 35:08.442
when she could barely move.

35:08.475 --> 35:10.477
We are family.

35:10.511 --> 35:12.713
‐ And as family,
I'm telling you,

35:12.746 --> 35:15.482
let this go and move on.

35:15.516 --> 35:17.751
That's what I had to do.

35:17.784 --> 35:20.454
I recommend you do the same.

35:20.487 --> 35:25.359
Now, I'm going back
to enjoy my grandkid.

35:25.392 --> 35:32.299
♪ ♪

36:08.268 --> 36:11.138
‐ Hey, I was just
going to call you.

36:11.171 --> 36:12.239
Hello?
‐ [cutting out] Boat.

36:12.272 --> 36:14.741
‐ Are you there?

36:14.775 --> 36:16.343
‐ Meg, there's
something out here.

36:16.376 --> 36:18.078
‐ Harry, I can't‐‐

36:18.111 --> 36:19.713
‐ Hello?
‐ Hello?

36:19.746 --> 36:21.648
‐ Hey.

36:21.682 --> 36:24.084
Hello?

36:24.117 --> 36:26.353
[gunshot]
Jesus!

36:26.386 --> 36:28.622
[gunshot]

36:28.655 --> 36:31.625
[dramatic music]

36:31.658 --> 36:34.494
♪ ♪

36:34.528 --> 36:36.396
‐ He's on the ground!

36:36.430 --> 36:43.370
♪ ♪

36:47.140 --> 36:50.277
[suspenseful music]

36:50.310 --> 36:57.217
♪ ♪

37:02.756 --> 37:05.158
‐ On the right!
On the right!

37:05.192 --> 37:06.426
[gunshot]

37:06.460 --> 37:08.395
He's on the move!

37:08.428 --> 37:10.497
[dramatic music]

37:10.531 --> 37:12.366
[gunshot]

37:12.399 --> 37:19.306
♪ ♪

37:53.273 --> 37:56.343
‐ Ah!

37:56.376 --> 38:00.347
♪ ♪

38:00.380 --> 38:04.151
[tires crunching]

38:08.655 --> 38:11.425
‐ Come on!

38:16.463 --> 38:20.734
‐ Agh! Agh!

38:20.767 --> 38:23.070
‐ Other side.

38:23.103 --> 38:26.206
[discordant music]

38:26.240 --> 38:27.207
♪ ♪

38:27.241 --> 38:28.742
‐ 3 o'clock!
3 o'clock!

38:28.775 --> 38:36.116
♪ ♪

39:16.523 --> 39:18.592
[footsteps] [uneasy music]

39:18.625 --> 39:20.594
‐ No sign of him.

39:20.627 --> 39:24.464
‐ Just keep looking.
He's gotta be out here.

39:24.498 --> 39:26.166
‐ Copy that.

39:26.200 --> 39:33.273
♪ ♪

39:38.078 --> 39:42.549
‐ This isn't how
it's supposed to end.

39:42.583 --> 39:45.319
You never stop.

39:45.352 --> 39:49.756
♪ ♪

39:49.790 --> 39:55.495
It's almost like...

39:55.529 --> 40:01.068
‐ Like what?

40:01.101 --> 40:02.736
‐ Like you want to die.

40:02.769 --> 40:10.043
♪ ♪

40:14.047 --> 40:18.085
Harry...

40:18.118 --> 40:20.087
none of this
will ever make up

40:20.120 --> 40:22.489
for what you did to Jamie.

40:22.523 --> 40:29.496
♪ ♪

40:30.430 --> 40:33.500
It won't work.

40:41.108 --> 40:44.144
‐ Any sign?
‐ Nothing.

40:44.178 --> 40:46.079
‐ Shit.
Just retrace your steps.

40:46.113 --> 40:47.781
I'll head over to you now.

40:47.814 --> 40:49.550
‐ Copy.

40:49.583 --> 40:56.523
♪ ♪

41:08.802 --> 41:10.737
[gunshot]

41:10.771 --> 41:15.642
[dramatic music]

41:15.676 --> 41:17.044
‐ Ah!
‐ Ugh!

41:17.077 --> 41:21.515
♪ ♪

41:21.548 --> 41:25.485
‐ [yells]

41:25.519 --> 41:28.422
[gunshot]

41:28.455 --> 41:31.124
[screaming] God!

41:31.158 --> 41:38.265
♪ ♪

41:52.112 --> 41:56.617
‐ Gah!
[groaning]

41:56.650 --> 42:03.991
♪ ♪

42:18.305 --> 42:20.240
‐ Harry!

42:20.274 --> 42:25.279
What the hell is going on?

42:25.312 --> 42:27.080
Got to get you to a hospital.

42:27.114 --> 42:29.149
‐ There's men after me.

42:29.183 --> 42:30.551
‐ Let's go.

42:30.584 --> 42:32.186
‐ Who did this to you?

42:32.219 --> 42:34.221
‐ I found something.

42:34.254 --> 42:35.756
‐ Okay.
Get in the car.

42:35.789 --> 42:39.660
‐ Let's go.
Let's go. Let's go.

42:39.693 --> 42:43.764
♪ ♪

42:43.797 --> 42:46.767
[telephone ringing]

42:46.800 --> 42:54.041
♪ ♪

42:59.780 --> 43:02.482
[telephone ringing]

43:02.516 --> 43:07.154
♪ ♪

43:07.187 --> 43:09.590
‐ What are you doing?

43:09.623 --> 43:14.461
‐ When your father gets out,
he should sleep at home.

43:14.494 --> 43:21.368
♪ ♪

43:49.796 --> 43:52.699
‐ I'll clean you up
in my office.

43:52.733 --> 43:54.601
Come on.

43:54.635 --> 44:01.575
♪ ♪

44:11.785 --> 44:13.287
[line trilling]

44:13.320 --> 44:15.222
‐ Hey, what's going on?

44:15.255 --> 44:18.659
‐ She brought him here.

44:18.692 --> 44:21.395
What do we do?

44:21.428 --> 44:28.335
♪ ♪
